Τ1115 interesting Document belongs to the time of Bishop Stapeldon. It was written on a blank page in Bishop Brantyngham's Register of Ordinations, etc., fol. 27. The Chapel of St. Laud (or St. Lo) was dependent on the Church of St. Mylor till the year 1868, when it was severed from the Mother-Church and became a separate Vicarage. On the 9ch of March, the day before the date of this Document, the Bishop held an Ordination in this Chapel and admitted thirty-four candidat-es (whose names are recorded in his Register) to the First Tonsure.—See Bishop Stapeldon's Εεῃὶετεϊ, page 459. ’
